<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-314-786  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 314 786.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  April 3 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Bell Atlantic seeks waiver to improve gateway.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Bell Atlantic Corp. (services).andO;Ticker:    BEL.andO;Topic:     TelecommunicationsInformation ServicesUnited States. Department of JusticeGovernment RegulationLegal IssuesTelephone companiesEnhancements.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>BELL ATLANTIC SEEKS WAIVER TO IMPROVE GATEWAY ARLINGTON, VIRGINIA, U.S.A,1990 MAR 30 (NB) -- In a tacit admission that its gateway trials inPhiladelphia and Washington have not been huge successes, Bell Atlantic fileda request with the Justice Department for permission to improve the services,making them easier for consumers to use and more attractive to informationproviders.andM;Specifically, the company wants a Justice Department waiver to provideconsumers with a list of standardized commands, to offer help lines socustomers can easily navigate the service, and to allow customers to createcustomized menus and pay flat fees for access to the specific services theyneed.andP;  In addition, the company wants the right to assist informationproviders in setting up services and to acquire the software needed to makedatabases work.andP;  Finally, Bell Atlantic wants the right to offer advertisingon the gateway, which is presently limited.andM;The Bell Atlantic Gateway was created in January 1989 after Judge HaroldGreene, who oversees the 1984 Bell break-up, eased the prohibition on thelocal Bell companies' entry into the information service business.andP;  It isavailable to consumers in Washington, D.C., Eastern Pennsylvania andDelaware.andP;  Bell Atlantic filed its waiver request March 22, and anyone whoobjects to the request has 21 days to respond, with extensions granted by theJustice Department in writing.andP;  Bell Atlantic would then have until May 3 toreply to the comments, after which the Department would either grant thewaiver or turn it down.andP;  In either case, the decision of the department wouldbe reviewed by Judge Greene, who could overturn the department's action ineither case.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19900330/Press Contact: Sandy Granzow, Bell Atlantic,703-974-3615)</TEXT></DOC>